{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608695/1958012801/0933.xml":{"full_text":"TN\nRambler\ni Browsts Happily\nIn GPO Bookstore\nBy GEORGE KENNEDY\nTin 170-page Congres\nsional Directory is one ol the\nmost useful of reference\nbooks for the Washington\nnewspaperman.\nAs a member of ths House\nand Senate Press Galleries,\nthe Rambler was given a\ndeckel-edged copy every year\nwith his name impressed in\ngold lettering on the cover.\nBut two or three years ago\nit was decided, and com\nmendable so, that reporters\nwho really want ths direc\ntory should pay for ft. The\nprice is S 4.\nYesterday, on learning that\nthe copy for the second ses\nsion of the ,86th Congress\nwas off the press, the Ram\nbler stopped in the book store\nof the Government Printing\nOffice to buy his copy.\nIt is the most unusual book\nstore\u2014full of bargains, a de\nlightful place to browse, and\nyou can get out with an ex\npenditure of 15 cents.\nThe Rambler spent more\nthan that after picking up\nhis directory. His old weak\nness got him, and he came\naway with two 30-cent cook\nbooks. \"How to Cook Oys\nters\u201d and \u201cHow to Cook\nClams.\u201d Vary Interesting rec\nipes.\no\nHE \u00abSO BOUGHT a 50-\neent copy of \u201cThe Capitol in\nBtory md Pictures,\u201d in\nmagazine* format something\nlike Lite, bn hearing that it\nwas almost sold out. And.\nknowing f*ma some recent\nunfortunate Incidents that\nhe should brush up on eti\nquette. he purchased a 30-\ncent copy of \u201cSocial Usage\nin the Foreign Service.\"\nHe learned that the book\nstore has 30,000 titles in\nI stock.\nWithout any advertising,\nthe store does a pretty good\nretail business. It grosses l\n$321,000 a year. It has\nbranches In the lobby of the\nDepartment of Commerce\nand In the United States\nInformation Agency. The\nthree gross almost $400,000 a\nI year.\nHowever, the OPO book\nsales are largely a mall order\nI business and the grots sale\nlis over $0 million.\nOne of the surprising\nthings the Rambler learned\nI is that the Government puts\nout about 200 periodical\npublications. The State De\npartment's \u201cForeign Affairs\u201d\nis one, and Agriculture has\nI scores of them.\nRight now the biggest seller\njis \u201cYour Federal Income\nTax,\u201d 35 cents. In Its many\nannual editions it has sold\nmore than 3 million copies.\nBut it will never approach\nthe OPO's all-time best seller.\nthe 15-cent pamphlet on \u201cIn\nfant Care,\" published by the\nChildren\u2019s Bureau. Over the\nyears more than 10 million\ncopies have been sold.\n\no\nYOU CAN BUY the pro\nposed $74 billion budget for\n$5 50.\nThe most expensive book\nIs entitled \u201cReference Radio\ngraphs for Inspection of\nAluminum and Magnesium\nCastings. Aeronautical Tech\nnical Inspection Manual.\u201d\nPublished by the Navy, the\nprice is $75.\nThe most beautiful book is\na publication of the Library\nof Congress. It Is a study by\nan expert of the Pierpont\nMorgan Library In New York\nof a 14th-century Illumi\nnated manuscript of the Bible\nIn Latin found in Hun\ngary. The frontispiece Is a\ncolor reproduction of a page\nof the manuscript In four\ncolors asd gold, a triumph\nof grapllc art. The book\ncosta 534 and 53$ of them\nhave beeb sold.\nAround, the big room oc\ncupied by the store on the\nNorth Capitol street front\nof the OPO building are\nmany of the categories of\nGovernment publications and\nthe best sellers In each divi\nsion. The best seller under\n\u201cPlumbing. Building and\nHeating\u201d is \u201cWood Frame\nHouse Construction.\u201d \u201cCamp\nStoves and Fireplaces\u201d has\na big seasonal sale. The big\nseller under \"Veterans\u201d is\n\u201cFederal Benefits.\"\nThen there are the lan\nguage guides and phrase\nbooks at 15 to 35 cents in\nabout 35 languages from\nFrench to Tagalog.\nWomen's Features\nClassified \u2014Feature Page\n11 I II iij)iMww.i\nI U f SKHE pi K nfIHKnIKHHHH\nIt ji Rj R I mmm m\nVims j| I -ifc jf'MlWnwLJt\ns. 1m Ar A Jk 111 m\nj. in\nKg p\nIB\u2014\u2014 \u2014j t\u00bb i\nSURVEY BUSINESS OUTLOOK\u2014Ab\nsorbed in the annual Business Outlook\nConference of the Washington Board\nof Trade at the Willard Hofei are (left\nto right) L. L. Hunter, assistant com\nmissioner of the General Services\nInterim Zoning\nPeriod Urged\nJustement Backs\nProposal in Talk\nArchitect Louis Justement to\nday urged a son mg transition\nperiod in which builders could\neither follow present zoning\nrules or the new regulations\nwhich are now under constd\ne ration.\nThe District Zoning Com\nmission is now putting the final\ntouches on the new regulations\ndrawn up by Harold M. Lewis\nand George Oatter The com\nmission's announcement of the\nnew regulations is expected\nshortly.\nMr. Justement. who thought\nit would be best to throw \u201cthe\nentire Lewis zoning report in\nthe trash can.\u201d also foresaw\nthe possibilities of compromise.\nHe addressed the annual Busi\nness Outlook Conference of the\nWashington Board of Trade.\nUrged by Committee\nThe transition period was\nrecommended by the Commis\nsioners' Zoning Advisory Com\nmittee. headed by Thomas J.\nGroom, president of the Bank\nof Commerce. Mr. Justement\ncalled the committee's recom\nmendation a \u201csimple and ef\nfective procedure.\" He laid:\n\"Let everyone proceed with\nconsideration of new projects\nand the preparation of plan*\nas though the new zoning regu\nlations were not imminent After\nthe new regulations and maps\nare published and adopted, new\napplications for building permits\nwould be received on the basis\nof either <a> the new zoning,\nor <b> the present zoning regu\nlations and maps, provided\nthat an Interim application for\na building permit were filed\nwithin 30 days after the adop\ntion of the new zoning.\n\u201cThe filing of this interim\napplication would require only\na sketch plan Instead of com\nplete working drawings, and\nthe owner would be given a\nspecific period of time in which\nto prepare complete plans suit\nable for submission with the\nfinal application for the build\ning pemlt.\u201d\nEffects of Uncertainty\nBecause of uncertainty over\nthe zoning regulation*, develop\ner* will hesitate to acquire land\nin the District. Mr. Justement,\nobserved. Those who already:\nown land for their projects will\ndefer their plans until they\nknow what the law will permit,\nhe added.\nHe also foresaw that some\ndevelopers, whose projects\nmight have been deferred for\nmore favorable demand or fi\nnancing. may have speeded\nthetr plans to get in before the\nnew regulations take effect.\nMr. Justements assigned\n.topic was. \u201cWill seeing cripple\nour growth?\"\nHis answer as applied to the\nwhole Metropolitan Area was\nno. He added. \"People, busi\nnesses and institutions are go\ning to continue to come to\nWashington for reasons having\nnothing to do with zoning. If\nthey don't find what they want\njin the District of Columbia\nithey will merely locate in the\nadjoining Maryland and Vir\nginia counties.\"\nResults Predicted\nPor the District alone, with\nthe original Lewis proposals or\nthe modified ones submitted at\npublic hearings last May. Mr.\nJustement foresaw these re\nsuits:\nA substantial reduction in the\nvalue of many downtown com\nmercial properties and in the\nvalue of land suitable for\napartment houses. Developers\nwould seek suitable sites in the\nsuburbs.\nSmaller assessment* and tax\ncollections due to lower land\nvalues, reduced construction of\nnew buildings on property al\nready Improved, reduction in\nsales taxes because of the re\nlocation of business beyond the\ncity limits, and increasing\noikoleacence of the city due to\nthe flight to the suburbs.\nCapital Boosters Work to Surpass\n'57 Record for Summer Visitors\nWashington had a record\nnumber of summer vacation\nvisitors last year and efforts\nare to be made to attract even\nmore this year.\nHarry L. Merrick, chairman\nof the Greater National Capi\ntal Committee, said today the\nSummer Jubilee staged ini\ntially last year \u201cwith precious)\nlittle optimism\" was successful\nbeyond expectations. He re\nported visitors totaled 916,000\nin July and SIB,OOO in August,\nnew monthly highs\nMr Merrick is president of\nthe advertising firm of Kal,\nD.C. Renewal i\nAids Economy j\nUrban renewal boosts Wash\nington\u2019s economy not only\nthrough construction and in\ncreased property taxes, but also\nthrough a variety of contract\nfees, area business leaders were\ntold today.\nMalcolm A. Burrow*, acting\nexecutive director of the Du- 1\ntriet Redevelopment Land i\nAgency, told the businessmen\nthat private contractors and\nreal estate men gain many mil\nlions of dollars through each\nproject here.\nAddressing the Board of\nTrade's sixth annual business\noutlook conference at the\nWillard Hotel, he said:\n\"The importance of the re- i\nnewal process to community\neconomy has normally been i\nrelated to \"the increased tax\nthat will accrue. The latest\nestimates for 'Southwest! proj\nects B and C indicate a six-fold\nincrease of assessed values.\n\"There is another benefit to\nthe community, however, that\nperhaps has not been suf\nficiently recognized nor ap\npreciated. This relates to the\neffect on the economy of the\ncommunity of the day-by-day\noperations of our agency. The\nacquisition of land, relocation\nof occupants demolition of\nstructures and installation of\nnew public facilities each serve\nto produce business and em\nployment opportunities in a\nwide area of operations.\u201d\nHe said that in Projects B\nand C atone, property acquisi\ntions \"have released $25 million\nfor re-entry Into the investment\nmarket\"\nj In the same proects, $1.25\nmillion has been spent for a\nnumber of contract services, in\ncluding engineering, demolition\nand relocation.\nU. S. Help Asked\nOn D. C. Tuition\nThe Diatrict Commissioners\ntoday agreed to ask State De\npartment help In solving a tui\ntion problem of 24 foreign stu\ndents at District Teachers Col\nlege.\nCity officials recently ordered\nthe collection of tuition of $253\nper semester from 24 students\nfrom Iran. Korea. Panama and\nJapan.\nTraditionally the Teachers\nCollege has not charged tuition\nfor foreign students 21 or over\nwho are living here. The city's\ninternal audit office ruled that\ntuition must be paid, however.\nCommissioner Robert E. Mc-\nLaughlin said he hopes either\nto have the students\u2019 visa status\nchanged to qualify them as Dis\ntrict residents, or to persuade\nthe Federal Government to pay\nthe bill.\nCONVENTIONS\nTODAY\nThe Evangelical Press\nAssociation, headquartered\nin the Raleigh Hotel, open*\na two-day meeting.\nThe Young Republican\nLeadership Training School\ngoes into its second day in\nthe Raleigh Hotel.\nBeginning a three-day\nsession, the United States\nChamber of Commerce\nlegislative congress meets\nI* the fits tier Hotel.\nWASHINGTON, D. C., TUESDAY, JANUARY 28, 1968\nAdministration; Malcolm A. Burrows,\nacting executive director of the Rede\nvelopment Land Agency; J. N. Robert\nson, director of highways; Louis\nJustement, architect and author;\nCharles E. Phillips, president of the\nI Ehrlich fit Merrick. He ad\n-1 dressed the Washington Board\nof Trade\u2019s annual business out\nlook conference.\n1 The $340 million spent here\nby tourists and those attend\nlng conventions he estimated as\nequal to the earnings of 84.500\n(\u2022persons employed in the Dia-\nI triet. if this flow of dollars\nwere shut off. he said, at least\n1 25 per cent of all Washington\narea business would be affected.\nClearing house statement*\nindicate that during Cherry\nBlossom Festival week, more\njl\nSightseeing Students\nOpen Season Earlier\nTwo busloads of New Or\nleans high school boys and a\ngroup of schoolgirls from Mil\nwaukee have already opened\nthe 1958 student trips to Wash\nington.\nThe traditional high school\nvisit to Washington at Cherry\nBlossom time\u2014last year bring\ning some 500.000 pupils\u2014ls\ngradually undergoing a change\n\u2014lt's beginning earlier.\nThe. New Orleans boys tour\ning the city by Greyhound bus\nare from a Crescent City high\nschool. They are stopping at\nthe Pennsylvania Hotel.\nProm the Holy Angeles Acad\nemy in Milwaukee are 85 girls\nand nuns taking a tour ar\nranged by the Baltimore St Ohio\nRailroad The trip will in\nclude a stopofl at New York\nand a visit to Canada, as well as\nseveral days' stay here at the\nMeridian Hill Hotel.\nFall or Winter Favored\nSlowly, said Don McDonnell,\nmanager of the student depart\nment of the Board of Trade's\nGreater National Capital Com\nmittee. student groups are be-\nWoit for Renewal\nProject Rejected\nDistrict administrative of\nficials have taken a stand\nagainst any moratorium on j\nbuilding improvements In the\nprojected Northwest urban re\nnewal area.\nThe stand was decided on\nyesterday by the Urban Re\nnewal Operations Committee.\nA subcommittee headed by J.\nJ. Ilgenfrltz. director of license\nand Inspections, recently made\na similar recommendation.\nAssistant Engineer Commis\nsioner Robert E. Mathe said\nthe recommendation will be\npassed along to the District\nCommissioners.\nThe decision was based\npartly on the fact that no\ndefinite renewal plan yet exists,\nhe said. He added that the\ngroup felt the District ought\nnot to discArage improve\nments In the area when such\nImprovements arP the basic\naim of the renewal program.\nThe ngenfrits Subcommittee\nsaid property owners would\nhave a reasonable time to re\ncover costs of repairs and Im\nprovements since the North\nwest renewal protect Is not\nexpected to be started for\nmany years.\nCongress Hears\nPlea for Tunnel\nCongress has been urged\nagain this year by an architec\ntural group to substitute a tun\nnel for the proposed Constitu\ntion avenue bridge across the\nPotomac.\nThe latest appeal to renew\nthe old bridge-tunnel fight\ncame In a resolution from the\nAmerican Society of Landscape\nArchitects, during a board of\ntrustees meeting here last\nweekend.\nCongress last year failed to\nresolve the bridge-tunnel fight,\nand the District Commissioners\nthis year have decided to push\nahead with construction of the\nsix-lane bridge at a location\nclitred by Congress four years\nago.\n\u00a7be \u00a7SBenin\u00ae |Rtaf\nmoney is circulated in the city\nthan in any other comparable\nperiod of the year, he related.\n\u201cApproximately half a million\nstudents visit the Capital City\nevery year, Aith most of the\nvisits comtng In the spring.\"\nMr. Merrick reported. \u201cTo make\nthe fall just as attractive a\ntime la obviously worth the.ef-\n1 fort.\"\nLast year, tn addition to the\n300.000 convention delegates.\nthere were more than 6.2 mil\n-1 lion visitors, he said.\n\u201cWe can do better In 1958,\"\n1 he added.\nginning to favor fall or winter\ntrip# here.\nThe advantages over the tra- J\ndltiona) March-Apri! sojourn,\nhe said, is the greater oppor\ntunity to combine sightseeing\nwith the educational aspects of\nthe visit. During the fall and\nwinter the various Government\ndepartments are not as crowd-\ned with sightseers as at Cherry\nBlossom time.\nMr. McDonnell said that dur- 1\nlng the fall and winter months 1\nhis committee can schedule spe\ncific appointments with various\nGovernment officials. He said\nthere is also more doing on i\nCapitol Hill than in the spring\nand summer doldrums.\n12 School* Pick February\nA spokesman for White House\nTours. Inc.. said the new trend\nIs definitely reflected in his\nreservations for February. At\nleast 12 schools have already\nmade reservations Last year\nduring that month the Arm had\nonly \"one or two\" groups ached- 1\nuled.\n1 A similar trend waa noted by\nD. C. Transit and the Gray\nLine Co. the two largest such\noutfits here.\nMr. McDonnell said his sur\nveys and requests for informa\ntion from chambers of com\nmerce throughout the Nation\nIndicate this year \u201cthere will be\nslightly more\" than the 500,000\nvisitors of 1087.\nFIRING OF ROCKETS\nBANNED IN D. C.\nAS SAFETY MOVE\nThe District Commis\nsioners today banned the\nfiring of rockets In Wash\nington.\nThe action was taken on\nthe urging of Police Chief\nRobert V. Murray, who\ncited recent Injuries to\nexperiment minded high\nschool students who have\nfired homemade missiles\nelsewhere.\nThe District hasn't had\nany regulation on rockets.\nThe Commissioners tenta\ntively approved a regulation\ndefining a rocket as \"any\ndevice containing com\nbustibles which on being\nIgnited liberate gases whose\naction propels the device\nthrough the air.\u201d\nDistrict Stiffens\nRules on Relief\nThe District Commissioners\ntoday approved sttfTer medical\nand vocational rules for public\nassistance recipients.\nThe city under the new policy\nmay deny relief checks to per\nsons refusing to get medical\ntreatment or Job 'training\nwhich might help them become\nself-supporting.\nA special Welfare Depart\nment Committee will review\nand decide individual caeea.\nThe city heads asked Cor\ni poration Counsel Chester H.\ni Oray to review the policy lan\nguage before making It final.\nThe change was recommended\nby the Public Welfare Advisory\ni Council.\nThe requirement for medical\ni treatment does not include\ni operations.\nWelfare Director Girard\ni Shea said the policy will affect\ni onljr\u2019about 10 current relief\nrecipients.\nEquitable Life Insurance Co., and Roy\nMundee, manager of the Richmond\nfield office of the Department of Com\nmerce.\u2014Star Staff Photo.\np i\nRoad Fund Loss\nSeen for D. C.\nRobertson Cites\nShortage in 1964\nThe District may lose mil\nlions of dollars for road build\ning because It cannot match\nscheduled Federal aid funds,\nHighway Director J. N. Robert\nson said today.\nHe said the District will be\nable to keep pace with the\nFederal interstate program for\n,the next five years But in\n1964. he warned, a shortage,\nlooms.\nThe shortage is indicated in\na recent estimate of road costs\nthrough 1971 made by the\nHighway Department, he told\nthe Washington Board of\nTrade's business outlook con\nference at the Willard Hotel.\nsss# Million Total\nMr. Robertson said estimates\nindicate \u201cthe total cost of com\npleting programmed improve\nments on the various Federal\nhighway systems through 1971\nwill amount to nearly $550 mil\nlion. The coats on the inter\nstate system alone will amount\nto more than $350 million\n\u201cSuiting July 1. highway\nfund revenues will be adequate\nto cover the District's share of\nthe program costs for the next\nfive years. However, in the\nsixth year, providing antici\npated Federal allocations are\nmade, a shortage of approxi\nmately $6.8 mUlion of Diatrict\nmatching funds will develop,\nand the ahoruge will be some\nwhat larger each of the remain\ning years of the 13-year pro\ngram\nWays U Carer Deficit\nMr RoberUon said ha has\nsuggested two means of in\ncreasing highway revenues to\ncover the coming deficits. He\ntold the Commissioners' Plan\nning Advisory Council it should\nj recommend:\n1. Retaining in the highway\nfund an annual contribution\n\u201camounting to almost $3 mil\nlion which goes for the partial\nsupport of the police depart\nment.\"\n3. Placing the toUl of auto\nmobile registration fees, in\nstead of the 34 per cent, in the\nhighway fund.\nHe stressed that the program\non which the cost estimates\nwere baaed is conservative. It\nIs \"not a cure-all for our traffic\nills.\" he declared.\nj* v\nsi aVv Jr-***\nT\" irini f\n\u2022H\nAll HONEST BOY'S REWARD\u2014Arthur Wong. 12.\nstands ready to cut a 25-pound cake at a party\ngiven In his honor by Mrs. Alice B. Cabell of 3711\nFourteenth street N.W. Arthur, who lives at 1430\nSming road N.W., found a MAO bill lost by Mrs.\nCAell.\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nLocal \u2014Suburban News\nRadio-TV \u2014Comics\nAction on Violence\nIn Streets Asked\nDistrict Must Give Protection\nTo Citizens, Hoffman Says\nDistrict citizens arc not receiving the protection frofil\nviolence in tbe streeU to which they are entitled, accordinf\nto Representative Hoffman, Republican of Michigan.\nIn supporting a demand by RepresenUtlve Keating. Repub\nlican of New York, for a congressional Investigation of tha\nhandling of the criminally insane, Mr. Hoffman said hia\ncolleague had \u201ccalled atten\ntion to the fact that the courts\nhave been turning loose a large\nnumber of criminals to prey on\nthe citizens of Washington.\u201d\nNet Getting Protection\nIn a speech to the House\nyesterday, Mr. Hoffman -de\nclared:\n\u201cOne thing is sure: The citi\nzens of the District of Columbia\nare not receiving the protection\nto which they are entitled.\n\"Day after day. at least night\nafter night, people are being\nassaulted and robbed on some\nof the well-traveled streets of\nthe city, and by Individuals who\nhave a well-established record\nof criminality, by individuals\nwho do not\u2014at least, on some!\noccasions\u2014deny their partici\npation in the charged crime.\n\"What these individuals and\ntheir lawyers say is that they\nhave not been convicted in ac\ncordance with the most technL\n.cal rules laid down by the\nj courts.\"\nTbe Michigan Republican as\nserted. \u201cthe individuals to\nwhom I refer have been several\ntimes convicted by juries, some j\nof them later released because\nof technicalities to which ap\npellate courts have called at\ntention.\"\nFavors Legislation\nHe said that he. as ranking\nminority member of the Ju\ndiciary Committee, would like\nto join Chairman Cellar in the\nrequests that the committee\nreport out some legislation.\n\u201cIt is apparent, and we can\nnot get around it.\" Mr. Hoff\nman said, \"that men who are\nguilty of crime anr who have\nbeen convicted of crime are by\norder of some court day after\nday turned loose to prey on\ncitizens here.\nSomewhat similar conditions\nexist to s lesser degree in other\nplaces.\n\u201cWhether the situation is due\nto the ignorance of the United\nStates attorneys, who do not\nknow how to present cases or.\nif that is not the trouble,\nwhether it is due to the deci\nsions of the Supreme Court or\nthe lack of legel knowledge and\ncommon tense on the part of\nthe judges of the United States\nCourt of Appeals, it is difficult\nto understand.\u201d\nBoy Proves He Needs\nNo Lessons in Honesty\nHonesty is not just the besM\npolicy, it's a habit with a small\nChinese boy in mid-Northwest\nWashington.\nAnd Arthur Wong. 13. of\n1430 Spring road N.W.. says he\ndoes not need any ancient Chi\nnese proverbs to prompt him\n\u2022It's just that I\u2019ve been\ntaught to be honest at home\nand at school.\" he explained\nsimply.\nFought Off Playmates\nLast Tuesday Arthur saw\nseveral teen-age boys grab ai\nmiddle-aged woman's purse\nnear his home. He ran for\nhelp quickly, and later sup\nplied police with enough infor\nnation for an arrest.\nLast Thursday he found a\nB\nj\nClosing his spech, Mr. Hoff\nman used these words:\n\u201cThe citizen has a constltu-\nI tional right to walk the street*\nof Washington and to carry\nwith him the funds for hia\ncurrent needs. The women of\nWashington have the right, p\nconstitutional right, to use tha\nstreets and the public places in\nWashington, and on those\nstreets and in those places to\nbe secure in their person, to be\nfree from assault or robbery\n\u201cThey have the right to\ncarry with them and retain\ntheir pocketbooks. From a prac\ntical standpoint that right ia\nnot now theirs\n\u201cThe Committee on the Ju\ndiciary does not needs to hold\nfurther hearings. Its chairman,\nits ranking minority members,\ni yes. every member of the com\nmittee. knows the situation\nhere in Washington, for ample\npublicity has ben given to It\nby the press\n\u201cWhat is the committee wait\ni lng for? Does it want citizens\nto am themselves in violation\nof the law and so protect them\nselves from the vicious crim\ninals who make the use of our\nstreeU hazardous?\n\u201cIt is just possible that. If\nmembers of the judiciary who\nhave been giving such a liberal\ninterpretation to the constitu\ntional provisions or member*\nof the committee on the judi\nciary should\u2014and we all hope\nthat will not occur\u2014have an\nassault or a robbery of some\nmember of their own family,\nwe would get a little more\nprompt action.\n\u201cWe are all inclined to giva\nquick relief when it affects us\npersonally. What are we wait\ning for? For some member or\ni a member of a member\u2019s\nfamily to be robbed or as\nsaulted\u2019\"\ni\nCatholic Scouts Meet\nLeaders of more than 78\ntroops of the Catholic Boy\nScouts and Cub Scouts will\nr plan their 1958 programs at\nI 8 o'clock tonight in St. Aloysiua\nt Parish Hall, 19 I street N.W.\ns The troops are sponsored by\nt the Archdiocese of Washing\nton.\n1100 bill in a street while skat\ning. and fought off a crowd of\nplaymates to return It to its\nowner.\nj Yesterday he shared his re\nward for returning the bill with\n'his friends.\nThe reward was a party, with\nice cream, cake and punch in\nhis classroom.\nMrs. Alice B Cabell of 3711\nFourteenth street NW\u201e who\nowned the bill, gave the party\nfor Arthur \u201cto show all the\nchildren that honesty is the\nright thing\nMrs. Cabell, a caterer, mads\na 25-pound cake topped with\n\u201cwhite mountain\" frosting and\npink lettering: God Bless Little\nArthur.\nCredits Playmate\nThe boy was too embarrassed\nto read the inscription aloud,\nbut not too shy to declare\nclearly:\n\"1 just want everyone to\nknow that Oliver was in this\nwith me.\" pointing to a boy In\nthe back of the room.\n.Oliver Mallory. 10. of 3479\nHolmead place N.W. modestly\ntossed the bouquet back.\n\"Arthur was the one who really\nfound It.\u201d he declared later.\nArthur said he \u201ctripped over\"\nthe bill while skating with\nOliver in Quincy street, next\nto Mrs. Cabell's house.\n\u201cI've been taught not ever to\nkeep what isn't mine.\" he said.\n\"Me and Oliver didn't know\nIf the bill was real or not. So\nwe headed for the bank to find\nout. We went in this alley,\nand there were about six other\nguys there.\n\u201cThey said. 'Give us that\n1100.' but we wouldn't do it\nThey all wanted a cut out of\nit. Then Mrs. Bowman (Mrs.\nIrene Bowman, a neighbor)\ncame up and said she knew\nthat must be Mrs. Cabell's\nmoney. So I gave It to her\nand went with her to Mrs.\nCabell\u2019s house\nMrs. Cabell said she wasn't\nsure where she had lost tha\nbill but discovered It missing\nwhen she returned home\nPraised by Teacher\nArthur, who said he\u2019 learned\nto share with six brothers and\nfive sisters, was delighted with\nhts party, but seemed mora\ninterested In making sure all\nhis friend enjoyed it.\n\u201cThat's typical of him,\"\nsaid his smiling teacher. Mrs.\nLucinda Allen \u201cHe\u2019s always\nthinking of others\n\u201cMrs. Cabell gave him a dol\nlar when he returned her bill,\nand the next day he brought\nIn 10 gznrs for thagMarch of\nD\u00bbes.^","height":"28777","width":"18240"}}
